John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are trained throughout Scotland, and where they strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen careers, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector that is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you are addressing his heart.”
This is convincing evidence that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams this year, we see that languages occupy leading positions in the league tables and have the highest score in terms of exam results in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade “A”.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an "A" in Mandarin (Chinese), while 72 percent of students received an "A" in German, 69 percent in French and 63 percent in Spanish.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that, among the reasons that created difficulties for employers in filling vacancies, 17 per cent had a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising job positions require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his further life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak well enough in a foreign language to support the conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage – spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is a fairly wide spread in terms of the languages that are taught – each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in light of the country’s future development until 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with a teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland seek to create a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what their future may be.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages remain vital for the future development of the country, and this should be reflected in education accordingly.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for Scotland’s youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edwards, Director of the Council of Independent Schools of Scotland
