North Korea says it will “categorically” not disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions heightened distrust of the United States and that his country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under any circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "substantial goodwill measures" last year, such as cessation of nuclear and missile tests, dismantling of the nuclear site, and an obligation not to build up nuclear weapons stocks and develop nuclear technologies.
“However, we are not seeing a symmetric reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be able to unilaterally be the first to take action on disarmament.”
While Ri repeated the already-sounding North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to the “stage” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea will be rewarded for gradual steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject the unilateral denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the incumbent U.S. president and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start a movement toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” by Trump.
North Korea seeks to officially end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to loosen tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists that ‘denuclearization must first take place,’ and increases the level of pressure through sanctions in order to forcefully achieve its goal, and even opposes ‘an announcement of the end of the war,’” Ri says.
“The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions increase our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were on the side of the denuclearization issue, not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been so.”
However, Ri’s tone was sharply different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim a “suicide rocket.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he does not set any deadlines for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months does not matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps that have been taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday, “The Security Council’s imposition of sanctions should continue actively and obligatory until we see full, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously intensified sanctions against North Korea since 2006, seeking to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip failed.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but within hours of that visit, North Korea condemned him for “banditry demands.”
North Korea pledged at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States took “appropriate action” on its part.
According to him, Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he spoke of were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore, as well as actions aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Rest in Special Classes
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all primary school students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine intake in order to wake them up “overnight”.
One of the academics found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he set fire to the idea of introducing such a course, having made a preliminary report on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl came up to me and said, ‘I’m very sorry that I found out about this just now that I’m almost finishing school.’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and sporting achievement, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was found that students were experiencing a severe lack of sleep during the study week.
The class lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One of the sections of the lesson offers an image of a room in the dormitory, where students, pressing on coffee cups, curtains, simulators and books, get information about how each of these actions and substances — coffee, light, which cause a lack of sleep — affect the amount of enough to get enough sleep, and how important it is to get enough sleep.
In another section, participants will learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just like any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health,” Professor Chassler added.
