A new study, conducted in one of the Scottish Highlands, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is to be hoped that the data obtained will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and will help in further activities to preserve the species.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland, will study ordinary non-pearls, non-pearls sopranos, as well as brown longhaired bats and Dobanton nightingales inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special loggers will be installed at some points around the site to track the actions of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys of the site using manual detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screaming, as well as the types of activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be compiled and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS’s nature conservation adviser, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the main areas of work on habitat management, such as meadow formation, as well as ways to maintain forests in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are in danger of disappearing due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose a danger, as well as flies adhesive tape, chemical processing of building materials, and the hunting of domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles in the way of flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bat populations very seriously.
