How a trade war with America could be useful for Beijing
Experts believe the first salvos of a trade war between the US and China have been overwhelming, and while the battle is still far from over, a split between the countries could benefit Beijing in the long run.
U.S. President Donald Trump made the first warning earlier this year, taxing major Chinese export goods, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation took place this week when new tariffs hit $200 billion worth of goods, effectively taxing half of all goods coming to the US from China.
Beijing has each inflicted equivalent retaliatory strikes, recently imposing tariffs on U.S. goods worth $60 billion in the amount of five to ten percent.
China has promised that retaliatory measures against the US will be equal each time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to start experiencing at least the slightest difficulty in the near future.
To force Washington to back down is to back down, but to publicly back down would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, according to experts, if Beijing is able to play its cards correctly, the pressure of the US trade war could provide long-term support to China, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
